# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-hd64180
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] In telecommunications and computing, **backward compatibility** (or **backwards compatibility**) is a property of an operating system, software, real-world product, or technology that allows for interoperability with an older legacy system, or with input designed for such a system.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Modifying a system in a way that does not allow backward compatibility is sometimes called "breaking" backward compatibility.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Such breaking usually incurs various types of costs, such as switching cost.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] A complementary concept is *forward compatibility*; a design that is forward-compatible usually has a roadmap for compatibility with future standards and products.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] A simple example of both backward and forward compatibility is the introduction of FM radio in stereo.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] FM radio was initially mono, with only one audio channel represented by one signal.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] With the introduction of two-channel stereo FM radio, many listeners had only mono FM receivers.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Forward compatibility for mono receivers with stereo signals was achieved by sending the sum of both left and right audio channels in one signal and the difference in another signal.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] That allows mono FM receivers to receive and decode the sum signal while ignoring the difference signal, which is necessary only for separating the audio channels.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Stereo FM receivers can receive a mono signal and decode it without the need for a second signal, and they can separate a sum signal to left and right channels if both sum and difference signals are received.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Without the requirement for backward compatibility, a simpler method could have been chosen.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Full backward compatibility is particularly important in computer instruction set architectures, two of the most successful being the IBM 360/370/390/Zseries families of mainframes, and the Intel x86 family of microprocessors.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] IBM announced the first 360 models in 1964 and has continued to update the series ever since, with migration over the decades from 32-bit register/24-bit addresses to 64-bit registers and addresses.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Intel announced the first Intel 8086/8088 processors in 1978, again with migrations over the decades from 16-bit to 64-bit.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] (The 8086/8088, in turn, were designed with easy machine-translatability of programs written for its predecessor in mind, although they were not instruction-set compatible with the 8-bit Intel 8080 processor of 1974.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Fully backward compatible processors can process the same binary executable software instructions as their predecessors, allowing the use of a newer processor without having to acquire new applications or operating systems.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Similarly, the success of the Wi-Fi digital communication standard is attributed to its broad forward and backward compatibility; it became more popular than other standards that were not backward compatible.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] In software development, backward compatibility is a general notion of interoperation between software pieces that will not produce any errors when its functionality is invoked via API.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The software is considered stable when its API that is used to invoke functions is stable across different versions.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] In operating systems, upgrades to newer versions are said to be backward compatible if executables and other files from the previous versions will work as usual.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] In compilers, backward compatibility may refer to the ability of a compiler for a newer version of the language to accept source code of programs or data that worked under the previous version.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] A data format is said to be backward compatible when a newer version of the program can open it without errors just like its predecessor.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] There are several incentives for a company to implement backward compatibility.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] One is that it can be used to preserve older software that would have otherwise been lost when a manufacturer decides to stop supporting older hardware.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Video games are the most notable examples of this, as it is most commonly discussed when discussing the value of supporting older software.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The cultural impact of video games is a large part of their continued success, and some believe ignoring backward compatibility would cause these titles to disappear.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Backward compatibility can also act as a selling point for newly-introduced hardware, as the existing user install base for the preceding hardware can more affordably upgrade to subsequent generations of a console.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] This can also help make up for the lack of titles at the launch of new systems, as users can pull from the previous console's library of games while developers transition to the new hardware.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] For example, the PlayStation 2's backward compatibility with the original PlayStation (PS) software discs and peripherals is considered to have been one of the key selling points for the console during its early months on the market.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Moreover, studies in the mid-1990s found that even consumers who never play older games after purchasing a new system consider backward compatibility a highly desirable feature, valuing the mere ability to continue to play an existing collection of games even if they never choose to do so.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Despite not being included at launch, Microsoft slowly incorporated backward compatibility for select titles on the Xbox One several years into its product life cycle.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Players have racked up over a billion hours with backward-compatible games on Xbox.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] A large part of the success and implementation of this feature is that the hardware within newer generation consoles is both powerful and similar enough to legacy systems that older titles can be broken down and re-configured to run on the Xbox One.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] This program has proven incredibly popular with Xbox players and goes against the recent trend of studio-made remasters of classic titles, creating what some believe to be an important shift in console makers' strategies.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The current generation of consoles such as the PlayStation 5 (PS5), Xbox Series X/S, and Nintendo Switch 2 also support this feature as well.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The monetary costs of supporting old software is considered to be a large drawback to the usage of backward compatibility.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] For video games, this also creates the risk that developers will favor developing games that are compatible with both the old and new systems, since this gives them a larger base of potential buyers, resulting in a dearth of software which uses the advanced features of the new system.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Because of this, several console manufacturers phased out backward compatibility towards the end of the console generation in order to reduce cost and briefly reinvigorate sales before the arrival of newer hardware.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The GameCube console has backward compatibility with the Game Boy, Game Boy Color and Game Boy Advance via Game Boy Player attachment.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Likewise, most models of the Wii had backward compatibility with the GameCube, however this was stripped out on later models released in 2011 onwards, also to reduce costs.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] Despite this, it is still possible to bypass some of these hardware costs.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] For instance, earlier PS2 systems had the core of the original PlayStation (PS1) CPU integrated into the I/O processor for dual-purpose use; it could act as either the main CPU in PS1 mode or it can up-clock itself to offload I/O in PS2 mode.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/backward-compatibility] The original I/O core was replaced with a PowerPC-based core in later systems to serve the same functions, emulating the same functions as the PS1 CPU core.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 2010, Hitachi Data Systems sold through direct and indirect channels in more than 170 countries and regions, with customers that included over half of the Fortune 100 companies at the time.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] It was a subsidiary of Hitachi and part of the Hitachi Information Systems & Telecommunications Division until 2017.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 2017, it merged with Pentaho and Hitachi Insight Group to form Hitachi Vantara.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Itel was founded in 1967 by Peter Redfield and Gary Friedman as an equipment leasing company and initially focused on leasing IBM mainframes.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Through creative financial arrangements and investments, Itel began to lease IBM mainframes to customers at lower costs, which led to Itel ranking second to IBM in revenues.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 1977, a joint venture between National Semiconductor and Hitachi formed, and was contracted by Itel to manufacture IBM-compatible mainframes branded as Advanced Systems.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] After initial success shipping 200 such systems and net profits of $73 million, Itel increased investments and personnel to market its Advanced Systems brand.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] When Itel requested lower prices to compete with IBM, the CEO of National Semiconductor Charlie Sporck, persuaded Itel to commit to long-term contracts with National Semiconductor and Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] When news leaked that IBM was releasing a superior line of computers, customers held back purchases of Itel goods, causing Itel's inventory to build up drastically.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi agreed to Itel's request to cut back on shipment, but National Semiconductor insisted that National had blackmailed Itel.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 1979, Redfield was forced to resign as CEO.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] National Semiconductor took over Itel Advanced Systems' sales and marketing divisions.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] National Semiconductor renamed the National Advanced Systems (NAS) division, assembling and selling IBM-compatibles where the central processing unit (CPU) was imported from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] National and Hitachi relied upon IBM's gradual and restrained roll-out of newer models to support IBM's technology and market share, which supported NAS's occasional successes.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] National Semiconductor and its subsidiary NAS were sued in 1983 by IBM for $2.5 billion on charges of using computer technology secrets stolen from IBM, as the result of an investigation by the United States Government into National's collaboration with Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi settled with IBM and licensed the mainframe operating system software from IBM.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 1983, NAS ceased manufacturing its line of mainframes (which had Hitachi processors) and became a reseller of Hitachi's mainframe and data storage products.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems (HDS) was founded in 1989 when Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) acquired National Advanced Systems (NAS) from National Semiconductor and renamed it Hitachi Data Systems.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Before that, the origins of the company had a history that stretched back to Itel, an early player in the mainframe market.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Intel's Computer Products Group sold National Semiconductors' IBM plug compatible mainframes.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 1979 National Semiconductor took over Itel and formed National Advanced Systems (NAS).
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] NAS shifted from manufacturing mainframes and began marketing systems from Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 1999, Hitachi bought out EDS's share, and HDS became a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] For many years, HDS sold Hitachi IBM plug-compatible mainframes and storage systems, but in 2000, it exited the mainframe business and shifted its focus to enterprise storage.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] On February 28, 1989, National Semiconductor and Hitachi announced their agreement that Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) would jointly acquire NAS for $398 million in cash, of which Hitachi would own 80%.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Memorex Telex and National had earlier, on January 10, 1989, announced plans on a joint venture "under which each company would own half of the unit and National would get $250 million plus four million shares of Memorex Telex".
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] By that time, Memorex Telex was able to arrange financing for the deal, but National had already accepted the Hitachi–EDS deal.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] The acquisition was envisaged to provide Hitachi with a better presence in the United States to compete with IBM.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] The entity was renamed Hitachi Data Systems (HDS).
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] On January 29, 1999, Hitachi announced it would take over EDS' stake in HDS, appointing Jun Naruse as CEO of its new subsidiary.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Naruse was an engineer with the RAID Systems Division who was involved in developing storage systems.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Having total control of the company, Hitachi infused Hitachi Data Systems with its corporate culture, ethics, and practices.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] On April 6, 2000, Hitachi Data Systems announced a re-organization to focus on storage systems rather than mainframes.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Shortly thereafter (June 26, 2000), the first HDS storage product was unveiled, the Freedom Storage Lightning 9900, featuring the crossbar switched architecture to interconnect memory, disks, servers, and other external devices instead of the traditional bus architecture.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In addition to HDS sales, HP OEM’d and Sun resold the 9900 and succeeding generations, which had additional capabilities such as virtualization of external Hitachi and third-party storage systems to form storage pools.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In January 2001, HDS announced the Thunder 9200, a mid-range modular storage system aimed at the small and medium business market, sold mainly through resellers.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems high-end and mid-range modular storage systems were complemented by software for storage management, content management, business continuity, replication, data protection, and IT operations.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 2002, Hitachi acquired Comstock Systems Corp, and analysts estimated that the acquisition would lead to a 35% percent market share.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] HDS moved to use the term cloud computing, culminating with an announcement on October 25, 2011.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In August 2014, in partnership with Avnet, HDS announced cloud partners.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] The corporate headquarters are in Santa Clara, California, with business offices in the United States, Australia and New Zealand, Canada, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] The culture of Hitachi Vantara is influenced by the values of Hitachi: wa (harmony, trust, and respect), Makoto (integrity, honesty), and kaitakusha-seishin (pioneering spirit and challenges).
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems appeared in *Fortune* magazine's "100 Best Companies to Work For" list in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and was ranked No.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] 8 in the *Fortune* list of top-paying companies in 2012.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Chief Executive Magazine gave HDS a ranking of No.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] 16 in its “40 Best Companies for Leaders” list for 2012.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems was recognized among the "Best Companies to Work For" in France and Poland in 2011.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] In 2010 Hitachi Data Systems was accredited by the Best Companies organization in the United Kingdom.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Synchronous TrueCopy causes each write to the primary volume to be performed to the secondary as well, and the I/O is considered complete only when updates to both primary and secondary have been completed.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Asynchronous TrueCopy stores time-stamped IO packets in the primary disk array and transfers them to the secondary array subject to link bandwidth.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] When the primary array's buffer is exhausted, it starts flagging tracks on the primary to be duplicated to the secondary when bandwidth permits.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems has four types of partners: Technology, Global Systems Integrators, Hitachi TrueNorth Partners, and Hitachi TrueNorth Advisor Partners.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1919/1920, BHP steelworks employees, General Manager Leslie Bradford and Chief Mechanical Engineer Jim Kendall and a group of their friends backed a racehorse named Jack Findlay that completed a remarkable sequence of five wins.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] With each win the group rolled-over their bets and by 24 January 1920 they had won a small fortune pledging their winnings to start a steel foundry business.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] On 28 April 1920, Bradford and Kendall used their winnings to establish the Alloy Steel Syndicate and build a steel foundry in Alexandria, Sydney.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] The syndicate was incorporated as Bradford Kendall Limited on 20 March 1922.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1926 Bradford Kendall began to manufacture railway couplers and undercarriages.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In the 1930s it entered the export market, manufacturing dredge buckets for use in Malaysia.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1948 the company was listed on the Sydney Stock Exchange.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In the 1950s foundries were established in Adelaide, Brisbane, Fremantle and Wodonga.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1970 a foundry was established in Port Hedland.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In December 1974 the company changed its name to Bradken.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] By 1978 Bradken was controlled by Australian National Industries (ANI) and Comeng.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1982 ANI became the sole shareholder.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In October 1990, the head office moved from Alexandra to Mayfield West.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In 1995 the business was rebranded as ANI Bradken.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] The business was included in the January 1999 purchase of ANI by Smorgon Steel who sold the business to Castle Harlan Australian Mezzanine Partners.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In August 2004 Bradken was relisted on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In November 2007 a new manufacturing facility opened in Xuzhou, China.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In July 2009 the business of Americast Technologies in the United States was acquired.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In July 2011 Norcast Wear Solutions in Canada and SwanMet in Malaysia were purchased.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In March 2013 Bradken opened a greenfield foundry development in Xuzhou, China following the construction of a manufacturing facility on the site in 2007.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] In October 2016 Hitachi Construction Machinery launched a takeover offer for Bradken.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] The transaction was completed in May 2017.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/bradken] On June 10, 2021, it was announced that White Industries had acquired the Ipswich site operations, a strategic decision by its parent company Hitachi Manufacturing to move its operations to offshore facilities.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The **HD64180** is a Z80-based embedded microprocessor developed by Hitachi with an integrated memory management unit (MMU) and on-chip peripherals.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The Hitachi HD64180 "Super Z80" was later licensed to Zilog and sold by them as the Z64180 and with some enhancements as the Zilog Z180.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The HD64180 has a pipelined execution unit which processes most instructions in fewer clock cycles than the Z80.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The most improved instruction group comprises the block instructions; for example those such as LDIR, CPIR, INIR and OTDR.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] This instruction type takes 21 transition states to execute per iteration; on the HD64180 it takes 14 t-states.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The on-chip DMAC makes block memory transfers possible at a rate faster than the LDIR/LDDR instructions.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The on-chip generator for wait states makes it possible to access too-slow hardware on a selective basis using a device filter, as is done for the TRS-80 Model 4's balky keyboard.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The on-chip ASCI makes it possible to implement additional RS-232 serial ports.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The HD64180 will not execute the "undocumented" Z80 instructions, particularly the ones that access the index registers IX and IY as 8-bit halves.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The Hitachi CPU treats them as illegal instructions and accordingly executes the "illegal instruction trap" behavior of resetting the PC register to zero, which simulates a cold restart by redirecting execution to the power-up location.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The Micromint SB180, SemiDisk Systems DT42 CP/M computers, and Olivetti CWP 1 and ETV 210s videotypewriters (also running ROM-based CP/M 2.2) were based on the Hitachi HD64180.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] The XLR8er upgrade board for the TRS-80 Model 4 also used it.
[src:hitachi-hd64180/hitachi-hd64180] On the Victor HC-90 and HC-95 MSX2 computer, the HD64B180 was used for its turbo mode next to the regular Z80.
